e the nuclear non-proliferation treaty.<br>
<br>
In accepted research computer simulations that have been used to explore and develop every facet of nuclear research since the limitations of the treaty were put into place.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Where is the experimental evidence for continued thermal heat blasts striking the pusher plate or any other materials?<br>
<br>
Where is the experimental evidence for continued nuclear detonations in space?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And I don't understand why you can't get past the 'space' issue..  There *is* no thermal effect in space...period. All that is involved is the force of the plasma-front against the pusher-plate.  The force of the plasma erodes the oil-coating of the plate..which is replenished between each blast..and, therefore, there is no direct involvement between the blast and the physical plate..ever...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Simply because a group of scientists got together with a good idea and put it on paper does not mean it would work. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh, would Einstein be laughing, now.. *lol*<br>
<br>
Speaking of..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Only two things are infinite, the universe and human stupidity, and I'm not sure about the former.&quot; <br>
-Albert Einstein<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
