 <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.whitetoweronline.com"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/barth-sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/30/03 1:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: well there we have it: an expert in our midst</span><hr size=1> Of course one can never know for sure if an Orion would work before actually trying it.  However, the laws of thermodynamics and heat transfer are well understood.  Whether the pusher plate will survive the thermal effects is an easy simulation and could be scaled down with reliability.  Thermally, there is no difference between a nuclear or a chemical explosion so long as the scaling is worked out correctly.  <br>
<br>
In fact, modern fusion research on the divertor (the heat sink and exhaust pipe of a tokamak fusion reactor) is much like this.  The plate has to withstand megawatts of energy being only centimeters thick.  Research in tokamaks (namely theoretical modeling on ITER and experiments on JET and D-IIID) shows that the surface can survive these intense thermal effects even factoring in the sheath effect which is a vital plasma physics component.  If we know the distance from the blast, obtaining the thermal input to the pusher plate would not be that difficult.<br>
<br>
The EMP effects of the plasma on the pusher plate are not as well understood, but plasma physics has come a long way in the past decade alone.  If there is any fault for error in the pusher plate, it will be here.  I think we need more information on a small nuclear blast and the impacts of the ionized gas on matter.  Simulations can probably do most of the work as we've learned a lot about nuclear testing from previous experiements.  Also, modern fusion research on the plasma sheathe (the thin layer between a plasma and a material surface where ions are accelerated and electrons are repelled) supplies a good place for modeling of an Orion.<br>
<br>
The targeting of the ship (i.e. will the ship fly) is merely a question of Newton's Laws of Mechanics.  These are well understood, so the issue should not lie here.<br>
<br>
Sputtering or erosion of the pusher plate is also an issue of the plate.  Like before, the plasma effects of the ionized gas hitting the plate can be calculated from reliable experimental verification in tokamak reactors.  This is a matter of building a plate thick enough.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately I don't have the numbers to crunch.  But doing fusion research with these extreme situations, I'd put my money on having an Orion drive possible. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/30/03 1:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: well there we have it: an expert in our midst</span><hr size=1> Is there anyone here who understands the linked document from the Federation of American Scientists?<br>
