<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> The EMP effects of the plasma on the pusher plate are not as well understood, but plasma physics has come a long way in the past decade alone. If there is any fault for error in the pusher plate, it will be here.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
This is part of what I’m interested in and would like to investigate further. Ablation of this plate is crucial. The plate cannot radiate the heat away fast enough before the next explosion hits. No known materials can handle temperatures of 80,000K from the plasma.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> I think we need more information on a small nuclear blast and the impacts of the ionized gas on matter.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I also think there are more factors to take into consideration, such as secondary radiation. Free neutrons and other atomic nuclei will travel through the plate thus increasing its atomic number creating a variety of unstable elements. The plate soon becomes structurally unsound.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Sputtering or erosion of the pusher plate is also an issue of the plate. Like before, the plasma effects of the ionized gas hitting the plate can be calculated from reliable experimental verification in tokamak reactors. This is a matter of building a plate thick enough</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Again, I have my doubts about this. All things considered, it wouldn’t really matter how thick the plate was, eventually it would become so unstable as to be unable to handle the plasma explosions for very long.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Unfortunately I don't have the numbers to crunch.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That information must exist somewhere.<br>
<br>
Again, thanks for the great response. Keep em coming. Of course, documentation on this material would most certainly help. Everything I've seen on Orion so far does not get into any kind of detail to make an informed decision as to its feasibility.<br>
