 from 1958 to 1965 can be  ordered from the U. S. Library of Congress.<br>
 <br>
So can the project Deadalas report of 1973- 1974.<br>
 Both can be  obtained as  very detailed written documents.<br>
<br>
 Between 1945 and 1963 hundreds of above ground<br>
atomic, and thermonuclear bomb tests were conducted before the 1963 treaty occurred.. Many of these tests demonstrated empericaly that some metallic materials can survive being close to a nuclear explosion, and remain completely intact .<br>
<br>
Another Example of This fact is a 1957 A-bomb test called<br>
Apple which resulted in a 29 kiloton Atomic explosion.<br>
This was done on a 100 foot tall steel tower. Most of the tower  about  90 % of it remained intact after the explosion.<br>
<br>
 Another Example of this occurred at trinity test site on July 16, 1945 in New Mexico.There was a 100 ton Steel ball <br>
Called Jumbo set up near it. Jumbo survived the 20 kiloton explosion 100% intact, and 100 % undamaged .<br>
<br>
  An Orion pusher plate system may easily have a mass of thousands or tens of thousands of tons of steel or titanium metal It is solid metal,  and it  may  be ten meters thick or more.. <br>
<br>
 More emperical  proof was provided at the Bikini Atoll Lagoon<br>
, in a series of three 20 kiloton atomic  tests from 1946 to 1948.<br>
<br>
 There were more then 100 decomissioned allied ships placed in the lagoon. After 3 explosions most of them still remained completely intact and afloat .<br>
Tim<br>
