<br>
I'll look for some online references to sheath physics.  I know of something for an online course on fusion as part of a class I'm taking.  I'll look through it and point out relevant parts.  Basically, you have 100 Million K temperature at the core striking a plate a distance of two meters away.  Of course there are electromagnetic effects so it does not follow a simple 1/r^2 relation.  However, this makes me confident this can be done.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately I have yet to study radiation damage in metals, so I cannot speak to this.  Since most nuclear devices do not consider this a major problem, it would probably not be so much as long as the plate was thick enough to last through the point ablations that occur.  Unfortunately, this is only a guess.<br>
<br>
You will need to keep the plate a certain thickness (i.e. not too thick) for heat disappation.  It cannot be too thin otherwise a few ablations would cause it to fail.  Sputtering and ablation are somewhat advanced topics but fairly well understood from the laws of classical mechanics and some atomic physics.  In other words, we can readily simulate these effects.<br>
<br>
Again, I'll look for what I can on the sheath physics. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 401<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/31/03 11:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   You're right. It's not possible, just because you say so.</span><hr size=1> Q66stang (3/30/03)<br>
